00:00:36.060 --> 00:00:39.054
going with new material.

00:00:39.054 --> 00:00:41.220
Today, we're going to talk
about frequency response.

00:00:41.220 --> 00:00:44.760
And just to set the context,
remember that last time we

00:00:44.760 --> 00:00:49.170
talked about a way to
characterize a system,

00:00:49.170 --> 00:00:52.980
in terms of a single signal.

00:00:52.980 --> 00:00:55.230
By knowing the impulse
response of a CTE system,

00:00:55.230 --> 00:00:59.010
you could characterize
the response to any system

00:00:59.010 --> 00:01:02.820
by thinking about the
response to any signal

00:01:02.820 --> 00:01:05.519
by thinking about the output as
the convolution of the impulse

00:01:05.519 --> 00:01:09.510
response with the input signal.

00:01:09.510 --> 00:01:12.030
And that gave rise to a
very compact way of thinking

00:01:12.030 --> 00:01:14.550
about the output of a system.

00:01:14.550 --> 00:01:16.380
We think about the
output y as being

00:01:16.380 --> 00:01:20.940
x convolved with h, regardless
of whether it's dt or ct.

00:01:20.940 --> 00:01:24.210
And the way that you
carry out that convolution

00:01:24.210 --> 00:01:27.420
is, in fact, very similar
in the two systems.

00:01:27.420 --> 00:01:28.980
That way of thinking
about a system

00:01:28.980 --> 00:01:34.830
is particularly useful for
certain kinds of systems.

00:01:34.830 --> 00:01:38.070
The examples we looked at
last time were optical.

00:01:38.070 --> 00:01:40.170
In the case of an
optical microscope,

00:01:40.170 --> 00:01:42.480
it's very convenient to
think about the effect

00:01:42.480 --> 00:01:48.070
of the microscope is
to blur the target.

00:01:48.070 --> 00:01:51.960
So whatever the target was,
it always comes out blurrier,

00:01:51.960 --> 00:01:54.210
and that blur function is
something that in optics we

00:01:54.210 --> 00:01:55.501
call the point spread function.

00:01:55.501 --> 00:01:59.520
The point spread
function in 6003 terms

00:01:59.520 --> 00:02:03.960
is simply the three
dimensional impulse response.

00:02:03.960 --> 00:02:06.060
We can think about three
dimensions very similar

00:02:06.060 --> 00:02:07.726
to the way we think
about one dimension.

00:02:07.726 --> 00:02:09.900
And in fact, in the next
homework assignment--

00:02:09.900 --> 00:02:12.840
which amazingly enough
is already issued.

00:02:12.840 --> 00:02:15.390
So in the next
homework assignment

00:02:15.390 --> 00:02:19.147
we'll think about two
dimensional signal processing.

00:02:19.147 --> 00:02:21.480
And the difference between
one and two is not very much,

00:02:21.480 --> 00:02:23.146
and the difference
between two and three

00:02:23.146 --> 00:02:27.910
is even less than the
difference between one and two.

00:02:27.910 --> 00:02:31.620
So we'll be able to think
about an optical system

00:02:31.620 --> 00:02:35.790
purely in terms of
the impulse response,

00:02:35.790 --> 00:02:39.180
and that's particularly useful,
because it's so intuitive.

00:02:39.180 --> 00:02:42.210
Since the effect of the
optical system is to blur,

00:02:42.210 --> 00:02:47.197
the impulse response is a direct
measure of how much it blurs.

00:02:47.197 --> 00:02:48.780
That's true, not
only for microscopes,

00:02:48.780 --> 00:02:50.520
but it's true for
optics, in general.

00:02:50.520 --> 00:02:53.640
Imaging with light, it's
a fundamental principle

00:02:53.640 --> 00:02:56.880
that derives from the
wavelength, the coherent nature

00:02:56.880 --> 00:02:58.320
of light.

00:02:58.320 --> 00:03:01.650
And here's an example taken
from the Hubble Space Telescope,

00:03:01.650 --> 00:03:04.050
where we see that there
is much more blurring

00:03:04.050 --> 00:03:08.340
from a ground based microscope
than there is from the Hubble,

00:03:08.340 --> 00:03:12.150
simply because the blurring
is the result of two things.

00:03:12.150 --> 00:03:14.910
Generally speaking, if you
have a ground based system then

00:03:14.910 --> 00:03:18.030
there's two kinds of blurring
that we usually think about,

00:03:18.030 --> 00:03:21.510
blurring to the atmosphere
and bouncing off

00:03:21.510 --> 00:03:24.600
particles in the
atmosphere, and blurring

00:03:24.600 --> 00:03:27.589
due to the optics, the same
as it was in the microscope.

00:03:27.589 --> 00:03:29.880
By going to space, we completely
eliminate the blurring

00:03:29.880 --> 00:03:34.350
in the atmosphere,
and so we're left

00:03:34.350 --> 00:03:36.960
with what can be a much
sharper point spread function.

00:03:39.247 --> 00:03:41.580
Today, we're going to look
at a completely different way

00:03:41.580 --> 00:03:44.010
of thinking about a system.

00:03:44.010 --> 00:03:49.210
Rather than thinking, what we
will call in the time domain,

00:03:49.210 --> 00:03:51.067
h of t was a function of time.

00:03:51.067 --> 00:03:52.900
The impulse response
was a function of time.

00:03:52.900 --> 00:03:55.540
We think about that as time
domain signal processing.

00:03:55.540 --> 00:03:57.290
Rather than thinking
about the time today,

00:03:57.290 --> 00:03:59.110
we'll think about
the frequency domain.

00:03:59.110 --> 00:04:01.310
Frequency domain,
just like time domain,

00:04:01.310 --> 00:04:04.750
is very convenient for certain
kinds of signal processing

00:04:04.750 --> 00:04:06.040
tasks.

