frequency analysis,

00:11:08.440 --> 00:11:12.504
is to think about the
input as frequencies.

00:11:12.504 --> 00:11:14.170
Think about the input
being cos omega t,

00:11:14.170 --> 00:11:17.260
and then think about
what the system

00:11:17.260 --> 00:11:21.910
would do to a signal that
was of the form cos omega t.

00:11:21.910 --> 00:11:23.680
We'll find out, as we
go through the hour,

00:11:23.680 --> 00:11:26.740
that the signal that comes out
of a linear time invariance

00:11:26.740 --> 00:11:31.330
system, when the
input is cos omega t,

00:11:31.330 --> 00:11:34.180
is also cos omega
t of frequent--

00:11:34.180 --> 00:11:36.740
it's a signal with
the same frequency.

00:11:36.740 --> 00:11:39.940
However, the amplitude
and the phase--

00:11:39.940 --> 00:11:42.010
that which sort of
addresses your question.

00:11:42.010 --> 00:11:44.000
The amplitude and the
phase can be different.

00:11:44.000 --> 00:11:45.375
Linear time
invariant systems can

00:11:45.375 --> 00:11:49.360
change the amplitude and
phase, but not the frequency

00:11:49.360 --> 00:11:52.060
of a pure sinusoid.

00:11:52.060 --> 00:11:55.810
So then the trick in
thinking about what

00:11:55.810 --> 00:12:00.010
linear time the invariant
system does, to a sinusoid,

00:12:00.010 --> 00:12:03.690
is thinking about how's
the magnitude to change,

00:12:03.690 --> 00:12:05.910
and how's the frequency change.

00:12:05.910 --> 00:12:07.620
So motivate that a
little more, well, I

00:12:07.620 --> 00:12:10.500
